00:02:40,950 --> 00:02:42,940
of the pre-Christmas season.

12
00:02:44,220 --> 00:02:48,519
First nighters, packed earmuff to earmuff, jostled in wonderment...

13
00:02:49,058 --> 00:02:52,424
before a golden tinkling display...

14
00:02:52,762 --> 00:02:55,889
of mechanized, electronic joy.

15
00:03:40,475 --> 00:03:42,271
Wow, there it is.

16
00:03:43,345 --> 00:03:45,778
The holy grail of Christmas gifts.

17
00:03:45,848 --> 00:03:48,748
The Red Ryder 200-shot range model...

18
00:03:48,818 --> 00:03:49,977
air rifle.

19
00:03:50,887 --> 00:03:52,854
And there he is.

20
00:03:53,356 --> 00:03:54,845
Red Ryder himself.

21
00:03:55,291 --> 00:03:59,590
In his hand was the knurled stock of as coolly deadly-looking...

22
00:03:59,662 --> 00:04:03,654
a piece of weaponry as ever I had laid eyes on.

23
00:04:08,370 --> 00:04:12,362
For weeks, I had been scheming to get my mitts on one of these...

24
00:04:12,474 --> 00:04:15,169
fearsome blue-steel beauties.

25
00:04:15,377 --> 00:04:19,608
My fevered brain seethed with the effort of trying to come up with...

26
00:04:19,681 --> 00:04:23,548
the infinitely subtle devices necessary to implant...

27
00:04:23,619 --> 00:04:26,815
the Red Ryder range model air rifle indelibly...

28
00:04:27,123 --> 00:04:29,488
into my parents' subconscious.

29
00:04:29,759 --> 00:04:30,725
Ralphie!

30
00:04:31,261 --> 00:04:32,227
Randy!

31
00:04:32,395 --> 00:04:34,225
Down here in two minutes!

32
00:04:34,631 --> 00:04:36,598
And I mean two minutes!

33
00:04:36,666 --> 00:04:39,133
Come on, Ralphie. I got here first!

34
00:04:45,407 --> 00:04:46,771
Cut it out.

35
00:05:12,534 --> 00:05:15,764
My mother, grabbing for her copy of Look magazine...

36
00:05:16,171 --> 00:05:20,470
would find herself cleverly trapped into reading a Red Ryder sales pitch.

37
00:05:23,312 --> 00:05:25,711
They traded Bullfrog. I don't believe it.

38
00:05:26,348 --> 00:05:27,507
What's that?

39
00:05:28,016 --> 00:05:30,813
Well, for Christ's sake, the Sox traded Bullfrog...

40
00:05:30,886 --> 00:05:33,012
the only player they've got, for Shottenhoffer.

41
00:05:33,155 --> 00:05:35,714
"Four Eyes" Shottenhoffer, a utility infielder.

42
00:05:35,957 --> 00:05:38,948
Got a whole goddamned team of utility infielders.

43
00:05:39,027 --> 00:05:40,425
That's nice.

44
00:05:40,594 --> 00:05:42,493
Ralphie, on the double!

45
00:05:44,131 --> 00:05:46,360
Did you hear about this guy who swallowed a yo-yo?

46
00:05:46,467 --> 00:05:47,728
Swallowed a yo-yo?

47
00:05:47,729 --> 00:05:49,128
On a bet.

48
00:05:49,203 --> 00:05:51,727
Some clodhopper down in Griffith, Indiana.

49
00:05:53,075 --> 00:05:55,804
They write the silliest things in the newspapers.

50
00:05:56,211 --> 00:05:58,838
What do you mean, silly? I mean that's real news.

51
00:05:58,947 --> 00:06:01,039
That's not like that politics slop.

52
00:06:02,150 --> 00:06:06,813
What is the name of the Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

53
00:06:07,522 --> 00:06:09,318
Victor. His name is Victor.

54
00:06:09,725 --> 00:06:11,216
How the hell did you know that?

55
00:06:11,217 --> 00:06:12,716
Everybody knows that.

56
00:06:14,395 --> 00:06:17,022
That's another one of your silly puzzles?

57
00:06:17,231 --> 00:06:19,562
Yeah, it's another one of our silly puzzles.

58
00:06:19,633 --> 00:06:22,999
Could be worth $50,000.

59
00:06:24,138 --> 00:06:25,900
What kind is it this time?

60
00:06:26,340 --> 00:06:29,467
Name the great characters in American literature.

61
00:06:30,244 --> 00:06:33,701
Victor? The Lone Ranger's nephew's horse?

62
00:06:33,948 --> 00:06:37,212
Meanwhile, I struggled for exactly the right BB gun hint.

63
00:06:37,285 --> 00:06:38,717
It had to be firm, but subtle.

64
00:06:38,954 --> 00:06:41,979
Flick says he saw some grizzly bears near Pulaski's candy store.

65
00:06:47,895 --> 00:06:51,728
They looked at me as if I had lobsters crawling out of my ears.

66
00:06:52,800 --> 00:06:56,565
I could tell that I was in imminent danger of over-playing my hand.

67
00:06:57,405 --> 00:06:59,304
Casually, I switched tactics.

68
00:06:59,974 --> 00:07:01,065
Hey, Dad!

69
00:07:02,376 --> 00:07:05,640
I'll bet you'll never guess what I got you for Christmas.

70
00:07:07,181 --> 00:07:08,511
A new furnace.

71
00:07:10,351 --> 00:07:11,908
That's a good one, Dad.

72
00:07:13,320 --> 00:07:16,550
My old man was one of the most feared furnace-fighters...

73
00:07:16,623 --> 00:07:18,385
in northern Indiana.

74
00:07:18,759 --> 00:07:21,488
Hurry up, you're going to be late for school.

75
00:07:21,796 --> 00:07:24,161
Yeah. I'm running late already.

76
00:07:24,432 --> 00:07:25,955
Round one was over.

77
00:07:26,834 --> 00:07:27,959
Parents, one.

78
00:07:28,102 --> 00:07:29,159
Kids, zip.

79
00:07:30,704 --> 00:07:33,570
I could feel the Christmas noose beginning to tighten.

80
00:07:33,908 --> 00:07:36,876
Maybe what happened next was inevitable.

81
00:07:36,944 --> 00:07:39,537
Ralphie, what would you like for Christmas?

82
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,874
Horrified, I heard myself blurt it out.

83
00:07:41,982 --> 00:07:46,008
I want an official Red Ryder carbine action 200-shot range model air rifle.

84
00:07:47,253 --> 00:07:49,186
No. Shoot your eye out.

85
00:07:49,255 --> 00:07:53,020
Oh, no! It was the classic mother-BB gun block.

86
00:07:53,460 --> 00:07:54,983
"You'll shoot your eye out."

87
00:07:55,228 --> 00:07:58,856
That deadly phrase uttered many times before by hundreds...

88
00:07:58,965 --> 00:08:00,932
of mothers was not surmountable...

89
00:08:01,001 --> 00:08:03,025
by any means known to kid-dom.

90
00:08:03,204 --> 00:08:07,003
But such was my mania, my desire for a Red Ryder carbine...

91
00:08:07,107 --> 00:08:10,371
that I immediately began to rebuild the dike.

92
00:08:11,479 --> 00:08:14,572
I was just kidding. Even though Flick is getting one.

93
00:08:15,249 --> 00:08:16,681
I'd just like some Tinkertoys.

94
00:08:16,750 --> 00:08:19,309
I couldn't believe my own ears. Tinkertoys?

95
00:08:19,452 --> 00:08:20,850
She'd never buy it.

96
00:08:21,287 --> 00:08:23,117
BB guns are dangerous.

97
00:08:23,189 --> 00:08:24,780
I don't want anyone shooting his eye out.

98
00:08:30,663 --> 00:08:34,496
Randy, will you eat? There are starving people in China.

99
00:08:43,944 --> 00:08:46,605
Mothers know nothing about creeping marauders...

100
00:08:46,780 --> 00:08:48,770
burrowing through the snow toward the kitchen...

101
00:08:48,849 --> 00:08:52,375
where only you, and you alone, stand between your tiny...

102
00:08:52,552 --> 00:08:55,281
huddled family and insensate evil.

103
00:09:03,162 --> 00:09:06,392
Save us, Ralphie! I just knew those bad guys...

104
00:09:06,466 --> 00:09:08,899
would be coming for us in the end!

105
00:09:09,802 --> 00:09:13,032
Don't worry, Dad. As long as I got OI' Blue...

106
00:09:17,710 --> 00:09:19,142
What've we got here, folks?

107
00:09:19,212 --> 00:09:22,146
Well, we figure it's Black Bart, Ralph.

108
00:09:22,514 --> 00:09:24,777
Well, just me and my trusty old...

109
00:09:24,884 --> 00:09:28,580
Red Ryder carbine-action 200-shot range model air rifle.

110
00:09:29,088 --> 00:09:31,647
Lucky I've got a compass in the stock.

111
00:09:31,891 --> 00:09:34,120
Well, I think I better have a look here.

112
00:09:48,074 --> 00:09:49,233
Oh, no!

113
00:09:49,709 --> 00:09:52,006
It's OI' Blue!

114
00:09:52,312 --> 00:09:53,710
Oh, no!

115
00:09:54,513 --> 00:09:56,104
Cheese it, boys!

116
00:10:08,194 --> 00:10:11,890
There's another one! He's a dead-eye, ain't he?

117
00:10:19,105 --> 00:10:20,662
Okay, Ralphie!

118
00:10:20,740 --> 00:10:23,833
You win this time, but we'll be back!

119
00:10:28,847 --> 00:10:30,245
Adi¨®s, Bart.

120
00:10:30,949 --> 00:10:34,611
But if you do come back, you'll be pushing up daisies!

121
00:10:39,558 --> 00:10:41,024
And don't you forget it!

122
00:10:41,093 --> 00:10:42,650
Well, son, you saved us!

123
00:10:42,728 --> 00:10:45,753
We were goners for sure! And you saved us!

124
00:10:54,240 --> 00:10:55,604
Oldsmobile!

125
00:10:56,009 --> 00:10:57,532
A pile of junk!

126
00:10:58,777 --> 00:11:00,971
That goddamned Olds is froze up again!

127
00:11:01,046 --> 00:11:05,846
Some men are Baptists, others Catholics. My father was an Oldsmobile man.

128
00:11:06,151 --> 00:11:10,211
That son of a bitch would freeze up in the middle of summer on the Equator!

129
00:11:10,589 --> 00:11:11,950
Little pitchers...

130
00:11:11,951 --> 00:11:13,250
Hold it!

131
00:11:26,638 --> 00:11:28,161
It's a clinker!

132
00:11:29,974 --> 00:11:32,100
That blasted, stupid furnace.

133
00:11:32,177 --> 00:11:33,507
Dadgummit!

134
00:11:38,750 --> 00:11:40,239
Damn skates!

135
00:11:43,155 --> 00:11:45,349
For Christ's sake, open up the damper, will you?

136
00:11:45,424 --> 00:11:48,119
Who the hell turned it all the way down again?

137
00:11:49,094 --> 00:11:50,117
Blasted!

138
00:11:59,771 --> 00:12:04,503
In the heat of battle, my father wove a tapestry of obscenity...

139
00:12:04,742 --> 00:12:09,110
that as far as we know is still hanging in space over Lake Michigan.

140
00:12:20,525 --> 00:12:22,924
Preparing to go to school was like getting ready...

141
00:12:22,994 --> 00:12:25,461
for extended deep-sea diving.

142
00:12:44,949 --> 00:12:47,150
Come on, Mom, we're going to be late!

143
00:12:47,151 --> 00:12:48,850
Just wait, Ralph!

144
00:12:50,087 --> 00:12:52,646
My kid brother looked like a tick about to pop.

145
00:12:52,723 --> 00:12:53,518
What?

146
00:12:54,725 --> 00:12:55,554
What is it?

147
00:12:56,528 --> 00:12:58,188
What is it?

148
00:13:02,167 --> 00:13:03,465
What is it?

149
00:13:03,466 --> 00:13:05,465
I can't put my arms down!

150
00:13:17,047 --> 00:13:19,606
Well, put your arms down when you get to school.

151
00:13:49,580 --> 00:13:51,069
Hey, Flick! Wait up.

152
00:13:51,215 --> 00:13:52,442
Wait up!

153
00:13:53,150 --> 00:13:54,207
So what are you doing?

154
00:13:54,451 --> 00:13:56,884
What does it look like I'm doing? Picking goobers?

155
00:13:57,121 --> 00:14:00,521
Hey, listen, smart ass. I asked my old man about sticking...

156
00:14:00,591 --> 00:14:02,990
your tongue to metal light poles in winter...

157
00:14:03,060 --> 00:14:06,460
and he says it will freeze right to the pole just like I told you.

158
00:14:06,697 --> 00:14:07,720
Baloney.

159
00:14:07,797 --> 00:14:09,764
What would your old man know about anything?

160
00:14:09,833 --> 00:14:12,130
He knows because he once saw a guy stick his tongue...

161
00:14:12,202 --> 00:14:15,796
to a railroad track on a bet and the fire department had to come...

162
00:14:15,872 --> 00:14:19,739
to get the guy's tongue off the track because he couldn't get it off.

163
00:14:19,809 --> 00:14:21,571
Come on, guys, wait up!

164
00:14:21,645 --> 00:14:23,134
Come on, guys!

165
00:14:23,614 --> 00:14:25,843
Come on, guys, wait up!

166
00:14:31,088 --> 00:14:32,486
I can't get up!

167
00:14:33,791 --> 00:14:35,553
I can't get up!

168
00:14:35,626 --> 00:14:36,557
Help!

169
00:14:37,995 --> 00:14:40,258
I can't get out! Help me!

170
00:14:41,664 --> 00:14:43,324
Come on, Flick, wait up for me.

171
00:14:43,433 --> 00:14:45,229
I can't get up!

172
00:14:48,705 --> 00:14:49,500
Come on.

173
00:14:49,572 --> 00:14:51,903
Get up. Sit up. Come on.

174
00:14:53,743 --> 00:14:55,175
You're okay. Come on, let's go.

175
00:14:55,245 --> 00:14:56,575
Come on, you're all right!

176
00:15:05,823 --> 00:15:06,789
Miss Shields!

177
00:15:07,791 --> 00:15:08,848
All right, everyone...

178
00:15:08,926 --> 00:15:10,586
take your seats, please.

179
00:15:18,635 --> 00:15:20,431
Good morning, class.

180
00:15:20,503 --> 00:15:23,835
Good morning, Miss Shields.

181
00:15:58,675 --> 00:16:01,074
Open your books to Page 32.

182
00:16:01,144 --> 00:16:04,010
And as you'll remember, Silas Marner...

183
00:16:14,489 --> 00:16:17,116
You're full of beans and so's your old man.

184
00:16:18,293 --> 00:16:19,522
Says who?

185
00:16:19,523 --> 00:16:20,522
Says me.

186
00:16:20,595 --> 00:16:22,494
Well, I double-dare you.

187
00:16:22,564 --> 00:16:25,157
The exact exchange and nuance...

188
00:16:25,300 --> 00:16:28,757
of phrase in this ritual is very important.

189
00:16:29,005 --> 00:16:31,564
Are you kidding? Stick my tongue to that stupid pole?

190
00:16:31,674 --> 00:16:32,640
That's dumb.

191
00:16:32,709 --> 00:16:34,676
That's 'cause you know it will stick!

192
00:16:34,777 --> 00:16:36,368
You're full of it.

193
00:16:36,913 --> 00:16:39,039
Well, I double dog-dare you!

194
00:16:39,582 --> 00:16:42,812
Now it was serious. A double dog-dare.

195
00:16:43,319 --> 00:16:45,479
What else was left but a "triple-dare you"?

196
00:16:45,588 --> 00:16:48,112
And finally, the coup de grace of all dares...

197
00:16:48,190 --> 00:16:50,589
the sinister triple dog-dare!

198
00:16:51,193 --> 00:16:53,752
I triple dog-dare you!

199
00:16:54,763 --> 00:16:57,230
Schwartz created a slight breach of etiquette...

200
00:16:57,332 --> 00:17:00,960
by skipping the triple-dare and going right for the throat.

201
00:17:01,036 --> 00:17:02,366
All right, all right.

202
00:17:12,081 --> 00:17:13,913
Go on, smart ass, and do it!

203
00:17:13,914 --> 00:17:15,413
I'm going!

204
00:17:16,085 --> 00:17:20,145
Flick's spine stiffened, his lips curled in a defiant sneer.

205
00:17:20,689 --> 00:17:22,656
There was no going back now.

206
00:17:25,694 --> 00:17:27,285
This is nothing.

207
00:17:31,666 --> 00:17:33,292
Stuck? Stuck!

208
00:17:33,368 --> 00:17:35,460
Stuck! Stuck!

209
00:17:41,376 --> 00:17:42,467
Jeez!

210
00:17:42,611 --> 00:17:44,043
It really works!

211
00:17:44,112 --> 00:17:45,544
Look at him!

212
00:17:55,891 --> 00:17:57,289
Ralphie, come back!

213
00:17:57,359 --> 00:17:59,258
Come back! Don't leave me! Come back!

214
00:17:59,259 --> 00:18:00,759
But the bell rang!

215
00:18:00,896 --> 00:18:02,587
What are we going to do?

216
00:18:02,588 --> 00:18:04,387
I don't know! The bell rang!

217
00:18:14,576 --> 00:18:15,837
Where's Flick?

218
00:18:17,579 --> 00:18:18,909
Has anyone seen Flick?

219
00:18:19,081 --> 00:18:20,809
Flick? Flick who?

220
00:18:20,882 --> 00:18:23,008
He was at recess, wasn't he?

221
00:18:24,652 --> 00:18:27,142
Ralphie, do you know where Flick is?

222
00:18:32,793 --> 00:18:36,193
I said has anyone seen Flick?

223
00:18:38,567 --> 00:18:40,193
Yes, Esther Jane?

224
00:18:46,274 --> 00:18:47,865
Oh, my God!

225
00:19:08,729 --> 00:19:11,219
Holy cow, it's the fire department!

226
00:19:18,340 --> 00:19:20,068
Wow, it's the cops!

227
00:20:12,560 --> 00:20:16,586
Now, I know that some of you put Flick up to this.

228
00:20:19,300 --> 00:20:21,859
But, he has refused to say who.

229
00:20:24,471 --> 00:20:27,098
But those who did it know their blame.

230
00:20:29,242 --> 00:20:32,301
And I'm sure the guilt you feel...

231
00:20:32,545 --> 00:20:36,503
is far worse than any punishment you might receive.

232
00:20:40,820 --> 00:20:42,946
Now, don't you feel terrible?

233
00:20:44,058 --> 00:20:46,890
Don't you feel remorse for what you have done?

234
00:20:49,296 --> 00:20:52,059
That's all I'm going to say about poor Flick.

235
00:20:55,102 --> 00:20:58,559
Adults love to say things like that. But kids know better.

236
00:20:58,639 --> 00:21:02,472
We knew darn well it was always better not to get caught.

237
00:21:02,575 --> 00:21:05,839
Now, boys and girls, I'm going to give you an assignment.

238
00:21:07,046 --> 00:21:08,740
I want you to write...

239
00:21:09,816 --> 00:21:11,009
a theme.

240
00:21:14,621 --> 00:21:16,918
"What I want for Christmas."

241
00:21:18,291 --> 00:21:19,780
The clouds lifted.

242
00:21:20,326 --> 00:21:22,725
And I want it handed in tomorrow morning...

243
00:21:22,795 --> 00:21:25,888
I saw a faint gleam of light at the other end of...

244
00:21:25,966 --> 00:21:27,830
the black cave of doom.

245
00:21:27,901 --> 00:21:31,927
I knew that when Miss Shields read my magnificent, eloquent theme...

246
00:21:32,005 --> 00:21:34,802
that she would sympathize with my plight...

247
00:21:34,874 --> 00:21:38,070
and everything would work out, somehow.

248
00:21:53,426 --> 00:21:55,893
Boy, did you see how it stuck?

249
00:21:56,462 --> 00:21:57,892
Did it hurt, Flick?

250
00:21:57,893 --> 00:21:59,692
No. I never felt a thing.

251
00:21:59,766 --> 00:22:01,192
It just caught me off-guard.

252
00:22:01,267 --> 00:22:02,694
You sure were bawling.

253
00:22:02,695 --> 00:22:04,094
I never bawled!

254
00:22:04,236 --> 00:22:05,702
Baloney.

255
00:22:18,851 --> 00:22:20,408
Scut Farkus!

256
00:22:21,020 --> 00:22:24,614
Scut Farkus! What a rotten name. We were trapped.

257
00:22:24,691 --> 00:22:27,591
There he stood, between us and the alley.

258
00:22:27,660 --> 00:22:30,719
Scut Farkus, staring out at us with his yellow eyes.

259
00:22:31,064 --> 00:22:34,294
He had yellow eyes! So help me God, yellow eyes.

260
00:22:49,815 --> 00:22:52,510
Grover Dill, Farkus' crummy little toady.

261
00:22:52,585 --> 00:22:54,074
Mean. Rotten.

